'''Arborsculpture''' is a branch of [[Arboriculture]] specifically involved with the shaping of tree trunks and branches into structures with ornamental or functional utility. Basic techniques involve pruning, grafting and bending single or multiple trees into shapes that grow thicker and stronger as they add annual rings. The closest related practice is Espalier.  
[[Image:Pretzel Tree.gif|frame|right|Pretzel Tree By Aharon Naveh - Israel]] 
The term Arborsculpture was coined in the 1990's to unify the field, but the practice can be dated back to 1911 when John Krubsack grew a chair in Wisconsin USA. 
[[Axel Erlandson]] is considered the most prolific Arborsculptor to ever practice this art. Starting work in the late 20's and continuing until about 1963 a year before his death.  Most of his works are currently housed at [[Bonfante Gardens]].  Serious arborsculptors can be found on each continent.   

